<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in labor mobility affect structural unemployment?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases structural unemployment</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreases structural unemployment</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on structural unemployment</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects frictional unemployment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Increased labor mobility reduces structural unemployment because workers can more easily move to where jobs are available, reducing the mismatch between workers and job opportunities.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the equilibrium price level when both AD and SRAS increase?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Price level definitely increases</option>
            <option letter="b">Price level definitely decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">Price level could increase or decrease</option>
            <option letter="d">Price level stays the same</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>When both AD and SRAS increase, the effect on the price level is ambiguous and depends on the relative size of the shifts in AD and SRAS curves.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in income tax rates affect the government spending multiplier?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases the multiplier</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreases the multiplier</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on the multiplier</option>
            <option letter="d">Makes the multiplier negative</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Higher income tax rates decrease the government spending multiplier because they reduce the amount of additional income that gets spent in each round, acting as an automatic stabilizer.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What effect does menu cost inflation have on relative prices?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Makes relative prices more accurate</option>
            <option letter="b">Distorts relative prices</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on relative prices</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects absolute prices</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Menu cost inflation distorts relative prices because firms change prices at different times due to the costs of price adjustment, temporarily misaligning prices between different goods and services.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
